body_html:
import tensorflow.python.keras also would not work:

python3.5 -c "import tensorflow.python.keras"
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: No module named 'tensorflow.python'

@ymodak I'd recommend you to familiarize yourself with the Tensorflow documentation. Ever since v1.9 tensorflow.python.keras is moved to tensorflow.keras.

Some further information:

  • I cleaned up the system and recompiled everything from scratch, but that didn't help.

  • I just realized that nothing from Tensorflow is actually working, even though it took around 3 hours to compile. Did I miss some installation steps that's not documented? For example:

>>> x = tf.constant([[-2.25 + 4.75j], [-3.25 + 5.75j]])
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
AttributeError: module 'tensorflow' has no attribute 'constant'

  • On my cluster, v1.10 and v1.9 branch simply gives too many compilation errors for me to solve them all, that's why I'm doing it on the master branch since it actually compiles.

  • I only know for a fact that the below commit from v1.6 would work perfectly for Python 2.7 on my system. I will try to compile that for Python 3.5 later:

git checkout `git rev-list -n 1 --before="2018-02-23 18:00" master`

body:
`import tensorflow.python.keras` also would not work:
```
python3.5 -c "import tensorflow.python.keras"
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: No module named 'tensorflow.python'
```
@ymodak I'd recommend you to familiarize yourself with the [Tensorflow documentation](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf). Ever since v1.9 `tensorflow.python.keras` is moved to `tensorflow.keras`.

### Some further information:
- I cleaned up the system and recompiled everything from scratch, but that didn't help.

- I just realized that nothing from Tensorflow is actually working, even though it took around 3 hours to compile. Did I miss some installation steps that's not documented? For example:
```
>>> x = tf.constant([[-2.25 + 4.75j], [-3.25 + 5.75j]])
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
AttributeError: module 'tensorflow' has no attribute 'constant'
```
- On my cluster, v1.10 and v1.9 branch simply gives too many compilation errors for me to solve them all, that's why I'm doing it on the master branch since it actually compiles.

- I only know for a fact that the below commit from v1.6 would work perfectly for Python 2.7 on my system. I will try to compile that for Python 3.5 later:
```
git checkout `git rev-list -n 1 --before="2018-02-23 18:00" master`
```
